This paper is about pedestrian detection using a novel autoregressive framework with cascaded phases. The proposed framework utilizes convolutional re-sampling layers to improve features while maintaining efficient memory and runtime cost. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper involves assigning strict labeling policies to each consecutive phase to improve precision, which suggests that it may also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also mentions that the proposed framework is designed within a region proposal network, which suggests that it may belong to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. Finally, the paper evaluates its proposed method on the Caltech and KITTI datasets, which suggests that it may also belong to the cryptography and security (cs.CR) sub-category.
